<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-09-09T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-09-09T23:00:00-05:00" n="1444" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1444">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">125.953/9–1049: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Tsingtao</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Hawthorne</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Tsingtao</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-09-10T12:00:00+08:00">September
                                    10, 1949—noon.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received September 10—4:59 a. m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>493. Lest Department misunderstand certain recent telegrams from ConGen,
                            we hasten assure Department we are not only willing but anxious remain
                            at post so long Department feels usefulness our activities, now largely
                            restricted telegraphic reporting, warrant continued expenditure
                            necessary Government funds.</p>
                        <p>Department pass Nanking its discretion.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Hawthorne</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>